Vladimir Poutine and the Risk of a Third World War
SAN FRANCISCO – Russia's invasion of Ukraine on February 24 marked the beginning of a third world war that has the potential to destroy our civilization.
The invasion was preceded by a long meeting between Russian President Vladimir Poutine and Chinese President Xi Jinping on February 4 – at the start of the Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympics.
At the end of this meeting, the two men released a 5,000-word document, carefully written, announcing a close partnership between their two countries.
The document is stronger than any treaty and certainly required meticulous preparatory negotiations.
I was surprised to see that Xi seems to have given Putin a free hand to invade and go to war against Ukraine.
He must be very confident and sees his confirmation as China's lifelong leader later in the year as a simple formality.
After concentrating all powers in his hands, Xi carefully prepared the scenario in which he will be elevated to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
After obtaining Xi's support, Putin has embarked on realizing his life's dream with incredible brutality.
Approaching his 70th birthday, Putin believes that if he wants to leave his mark on Russian history, it's now or never.
But his vision of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
He seems to believe that the Russian people need a tsar whom they can follow blindly.
This is precisely the opposite of a democratic society - and it is a vision that distorts the "soul" of Russia, emotional to the point of sensitivity.
As a child, I met Russian soldiers many times when they occupied Hungary in 1945.
I learned that they were willing to share their last piece of bread with you if you asked them.
Later, at the beginning of the 1980s, I embarked on what I call my political philanthropy.
First, I created a foundation in my native Hungary, then I actively participated in the disintegration of the Soviet Empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, the disintegration had already begun.
I created a foundation in Russia, then did the same in each of the successor states.
In Ukraine, I created a foundation even before it became an independent country.
I also visited China in 1984, where I was the first foreigner authorized to establish a foundation (which I closed in 1989, just before the Tiananmen Square massacre).
I do not know Putin personally, but I have closely observed his rise, being fully aware of his cruelty.
He has reduced the capital of Chechnya, Grozny, to rubble. And he threatens to do the same with the capital of Ukraine, Kyiv.
Putin was once a clever operator of the KGB, but he seems to have changed recently.
Having developed a fixed idea, he seems to have lost touch with reality.
He has certainly misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He expected that Russian-speaking Ukrainians would welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but they turned out to be completely on the same positions as the Ukrainian-speaking population.
The Ukrainians have set up an incredibly courageous resistance against an opponent that seems to be unstoppable.
In July 2021, Putin published a long essay arguing that Russians and Ukrainians are really one people and that Ukrainians have been tricked by neo-Nazi agitators.
The first part of his argument is not without historical justification, given that Kyiv was the original seat of the Russian Orthodox Church.
But in the second part, it was Putin who was misled.
He should have been more cautious.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely during the 'Euromaidan' protests in 2014.
The events of 2014 plunged him into a fit of black rage.
But the Russian army performed poorly when it was ordered to attack its Ukrainian brothers.
Deep-rooted corruption in the awarding of defense contracts also played an important role in his insufficient results.
Yet, instead of blaming himself, Putin seems to have literally gone mad.
He decided to punish Ukraine for opposing him and seems to be acting without encountering any resistance.
He is sending the entire Russian army into battle and ignoring all the rules of war, including bombing the civilian population indiscriminately.
Many hospitals were hit and the power grid supplying the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (currently occupied by Russian troops) was damaged.
In the besieged Marioupol, 400,000 people went without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia may well lose the war.
The United States and the European Union are sending defensive weapons to Ukraine, and efforts are underway to purchase Russian-made MIG fighters, which Ukrainian pilots know how to fly.
This could make all the difference.
Regardless of the outcome, Putin has already done wonders in strengthening the determination and unity of the EU.
Meanwhile, Xi seems to have realized that Putin is acting on his own.
On March 8, a day after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi insisted that the friendship between China and Russia remain "solid," Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz to say that he supports their efforts to restore peace.
He wished to express maximum restraint in the war to avoid a humanitarian crisis.
It is far from certain that Putin will heed Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be removed before they destroy our civilization.
